The Giants aren't the Bills ranking 25th in DVOA, giving up the fourth-highest catch rate and ninth-most receptions to the position.

Ertz is the TE5 in fantasy points per game with a 19.8% target share (fifth) and 20.2% air yard share (fourth). He's garnered the second-most red zone targets at the position. He's 22nd in yards per route run and 14th in PFF receiving grade (minimum ten targets). Ertz is another must-start player this week from this game. Seattle is 32nd in DVOA against tight ends allowing the second-most receiving yards. The Seahawks have given up the highest yards per reception and most fantasy points per game to tight ends.

Goedert is so underappreciated. He's the TE6 in fantasy points per game and a metric behemoth. I love drooling over his stats weekly. He's sixth in target share, 12th in target per route run rate, and second in yards per route run. He's an elite YAC producer. Elite. Among all wide receivers and tight ends with ten or more targets, he's first in YAC per reception and first in YAC. He's 18 yards after the catch better than Cooper Kupp. Yep. You read that correctly. Dallas has been tough on opposing tight ends ranking ninth in DVOA with the fourth-fewest receiving yards and lowest yards per reception allowed. Honestly. I could care less. They have faced Cameron Brate, Hayden Hurst, Logan Thomas, Daniel Bellinger, and Tyler Higbee. None of these tight ends are in Goedert's talent area code. None of them. Goedert will crush again this week.

Captain's log. "The year is 2022. I've arrived in this strange land where Tyler Higbee is tied with Mark Andrews for the most targets for a tight end." Yes, it's true. Higbee has been eye-opening this year. He's the TE7 in fantasy, ranking ninth in yards per route run (second-highest of his career) and fourth in receiving yards. Higbee is a top-three tight end this week against a Panthers defense that's 24th in DVOA with the second-highest catch rate and ninth-most receiving touchdowns (tied) allowed to tight ends. Higbee has been listed as questionable (ankle), but he's expected to play after back-to-back limited practices to close out the week.

Kittle has been a resounding disappointment this year. He's the TE28 in fantasy points per game, averaging only five targets, 3.7 receptions, and 33 receiving yards per game. Those numbers are nauseating, and we can point to usage, but Kittle's efficiency has also declined. He's 20th in PFF receiving grade, 17th in yards per route run, and 32nd in YAC per reception (minimum ten targets). Kittle is presented with another solid matchup this week, but it's questionable whether he can or will be allowed to take advantage of it. Atlanta has allowed the third-most receiving yards, eighth-highest catch rate, and fifth-most fantasy points to inline tight ends (Kittle 58.9% inline). Kittle remains a TE1 and must-start, reflecting more of the tight-end position than Kittle's production.

Njoku is currently crushing as the TE8 in fantasy. He's second in PFF receiving grade, third in yards per route run, and first in target per route run rate (minimum ten targets). He's fourth in red zone targets, but so far only has one touchdown to his credit. That could change this week. The Patriots are eighth in DVOA but have allowed the most receiving touchdowns (five) to tight ends. Njoku is also fifth in YAC and now faces a Patriots defense that's fifth in missed tackles. Njoku is a top-ten TE option.

Everett is the TE9 in fantasy points per game. He has a 15.7% target share (11th), 69.0% route participation (15th), and ranks eighth in routes run. He's tenth among tight ends in red zone targets (four). Denver is a worrisome assignment for tight ends, ranking fifth in DVOA and 19th in receiving yards and yards per reception allowed. Everett is a low-end TE1.

Hurst has been a profitable streaming option all season who now sits at TE11 in fantasy scoring. This week he falls to TE2 territory against the Saints. Hurst has a 14.8% target share (14th) while ranking seventh in routes run and ninth in route participation. While his red zone role (fifth in red zone targets) has been healthy, his efficiency has been about what you'd expect (30th in yards per route run). The Saints eat tight ends alive in coverage. New Orleans is second in DVOA with the second-lowest catch rate and eighth-fewest receiving yards allowed.

Engram is a TE1 this week. He's been an inefficient route monster. He's cobbled together two top 12 weeks based on his high route rate and volume. He's 13th in target share (15.0%), tenth in routes run, and 14th in route participation (71.4%). He's also top ten in air yard share and deep targets. All of these areas are fantastic, but here are the warts. He's only seen two red zone targets (21st) and has 1.30 yards per route run (19th). With his volume and a plus matchup in Week 6, he should find his way inside the top 12. Indy is 26th in DVOA, allowing the eighth-most receptions, 11th-most receiving yards, and fourth-most receiving touchdowns to the position.
Pitts missed last week's game with a hamstring injury. Check back Friday to see if he can suit up in Week 6.

Hill has been feast or famine. He has finished as the TE3, TE50, TE16, and TE1. Hill shouldn't be listed as a tight end, but that's a battle for a different day. He's run a total of 14 routes all season while catching one pass for two yards. The bulk of his production has come via rushing, with 5.3 carries and 57 rushing yards per game (1.3 touchdowns per game). Toss a dart with Hill in your tight end spot if you need the upside, but he's a risky TE2.

Tonyan is low-end TE2. Over the last two games, he's only seen an 8.6% target share with a 57.1% route run clip. That's not nearly good enough against a Jets' defense that's 14th in DVOA, allowing the eighth-lowest catch rate to the position.

If Fant and Dissly are both on the waiver wire and you're flipping a coin on which to stream this week, I lean slightly in Dissly's favor. Dissly has been slightly more efficient with his target volume besting Fant in yards per route run (1.78 vs. 1.18) and YAC per reception (4.8 vs. 3.1). Stream Dissly if you need a tight end this week.

This isn't the week to stream Conklin. With Wilson back, his 11.1% target share has amounted to three targets per game. Over the last two games, his route run rate has declined to 56.2%. The Packers are 12th in DVOA against tight ends allowing the second-fewest receiving yards.

Despite his 14% target share and 84.5% route run rate, Kmet is only a desperate TE2 target. His target share has only amounted to 2.4 targets per game. He's been held below 20 receiving yards in three of five games. Washington is 15th in DVOA, facing the third-fewest tight end targets and yielding the sixth-fewest receiving yards.

Without Smith last week Henry played 98% of the snaps with a 23.2% target share and 95.2% route participation clip. His five targets and 54 receiving yards were both season-highs. If Smith is out again, Henry is a deep league streamer. The Browns are a tough matchup for tight ends ranking sixth in DVOA allowing the lowest catch rate to the position.

Both of these Seattle tight ends are streamer worthy this week. The matchup is that good. These two have split the receiving role weekly and shared the field on many plays. SEA has utilized 12 personnel at the fourth-highest rate, which means both of these players will see plenty of snaps. Arizona is 30th in DVOA against tight ends allowing the fifth-highest catch rate, seventh-best yards per reception, and second-most fantasy points per game.

If you're in a pinch, and I do mean PINCH. Gesicki is a panic mode streamer option this week. Over the last two weeks, he's been reintegrated into this offense with 59% and 66.7% route run rates. The problem is that he's only drawn a 9% target share which has amounted to 1.5 receptions and 26.5 receiving yards per game. His numbers are ugly, but the matchup against Minnesota is beautiful. They are 28th in DVOA against tight ends allowing the highest catch rate, tenth-highest receiving yards, 11th-best yards per reception, and 10th-highest fantasy points to slot tight ends (Gesicki 56.4% slot over the last two games). Add in that Tyreek Hill is banged up, and Gesicki could get a bump in the passing game this week.
Knox missed last game with foot and hamstring issues. We'll see on Friday if he's able to make it back for this big game.
Brate has returned to practice after missing last week's game with a concussion. I lean toward him playing this week. Brate is a low-end TE2 if he returns.

Myles may not have many opportunities to rush against a team that will run the ball whenever possible but still checks in as the top DL option of Week 6. Despite their preference for the run, New England has allowed the 13th most fantasy points to the position.

Trey Hendrickson played just 68 percent of the snaps in Week 5 against Baltimore, a concerning sign if this usage keeps up. Hendrickson played over 83 percent of the snaps in three of five games this season but is going to be hard to trust if he can drop to 63 percent or below without any notice. The most concerning part is that he is losing snaps to Cameron Sample and not dynasty darling Joseph Ossai. Sample is better as a run-stopper, which means Hendrickson may see a reduced role on early downs going forward. This is a disturbing development for a player who was already pretty sack-dependent. He is still in the DL2 conversation but should no longer be tapped as a DL1 option. With a tough matchup against his former team on tap for Week 6, Hendrickson should be viewed as more of a DL3 option than a DL2. Keep him benched if you are required to start fewer than three DLs weekly.

Rousseau was in on a concerningly few third down snaps in Week 5, but we will chalk that up to gamescript. Rousseau remains a DL1 option for Week 6 against a Kansas City Chiefs team allowing the ninth most fantasy points to the position.

Montez Sweat had a monster Week 5, recording five solos, one assist, two sacks, and three tackles for loss. The sacks are his firsts of the season but he is heating up at just the right time. Sweat is a DL1 option when he is at his best and has help coming in the next few weeks in the form of Chase Young. Sweat is back to being a high-end DE2 option for a plus Week 6 matchup against a Chicago Bears team relinquishing the 14th most fantasy points to opposing edge rushers. Sweat should be started in all competitive formats.

Zach Allen was at it again in Week 5, tallying five solos, three assists, one sack, one tackle for loss, and one pass defended. He recorded a sack for the second straight game and now has five passes defended in his last three contests. He plays most of his snaps as a defensive tackle or defensive end in an odd front, so there is little chance that he can stay hot all season, but he seems to be coming into his own and to be scratching the surface of his potential. He is an obvious option for DT leagues but has some bye week value as a DE option as well. Consider him a DT1/DL3 option for a plus Week 6 matchup against a Seattle Seahawks team surrendering the 12th most fantasy points per game to the position.

Lawson recorded a sack for the second straight game in Week 5, posting one solo, one assist, one sack, one tackle for loss, and one forced fumble. Lawson started the season slowly but seems to be turning it on just in time for the byes. The Week 6 matchup is not ideal, as the Green Bay Packers have limited the position to the seventh fewest fantasy points, but for those who find themselves in a bye week or injury-related pinch, Lawson makes for a strong DL4/flex option.

Yannick was solid in Week 5, recording one solo, one assist, 1.5 sacks, and one tackle for loss. The veteran pass rusher has been inconsistent this season but now has 2.5 sacks in his last three games and could be heating up. Ngakoue has two sacks in two contests against his former team, but both came as a member of the Ravens defensive front. He was blanked against Jacksonville back in Week 2. The matchup is a neutral one on paper, so this play is more about his recent form than the opponent itself. Ngakoue will be a little sack-dependent this weekend, so the absence of Kwity Paye could play a factor. Start Ngakoue as a borderline DL2 option for Week 6.

Dexter went off in Week 5, tallying four solos, one assist, one sack, and one tackle for loss. The noted run-stopper and unusual tackle provider for a defensive tackle eligible player now has three sacks in his last two games, catapulting him into the DL2 conversation for Week 6. Already just one sack off of his career high, Dexter looks to have taken his fantasy game to the next level under Wink Martindale. Plug him in as a DT1/DE2 option for a plus Week 6 matchup against Lamar Jackson and Wink's former team in the Ravens. His familiarity with the offense should make it a long afternoon for the Ravens offensive line.

Yetur continues to play starters snaps alongside Brian Burns but still has nothing to show for it, recording zero sacks and just one tackle for loss. He showed some promise with his 3.5 sacks last season and was expected to take a major leap with Haason Reddick now plying his wares in Philadelphia. Unfortunately, that has not happened, and it might not change this week despite a dream matchup against a Los Angeles Rams offensive line that has been a turnstile all season. Keep the Penn State product benched despite facing a Rams team allowing the third most fantasy points to the position.

Dayo is in line to get the start this weekend if Kwity Paye is ruled out as expected. He is worth a start as a DL3/DL4 option for those who may find themselves in a bye-week pinch. Other managers should take a wait-and-see approach.
Franklin-Myers should see an expanded role with Jermaine Johnson ruled out. Given roughly 70 percent of the snaps, Myers boasts DL3 value for a tough Week 6 matchup against the Green Bay Packers.
Omenihu is set to see an expanded role against the Falcons due to Nick Bosa being sidelined. He is worth a look as a deep league DL3 option for a plus Week 6 matchup against the Atlanta Falcons.

Drake has seen his snaps increase in each of the last four weeks and is playing more inside with Arik Armstead sidelined. The injury may be the opportunity the rookie needs to stake his claim on a larger role in the rotation.  He is worth a look in the deepest of DT leagues.
Roquan is a top-three option for Week 6. He is the DL3 overall on the season and has a tasty matchup against a Commanders offense allowing the sixth most fantasy points to the position.
White is a top-five option for a plus matchup against a struggling Pittsburgh Steelers team. Lock him in as an IDP1.

After a slow start to the season, Foyesade is back upon the LB1 overall throne. Oluokun recorded six solos, two assists, one sack, and one tackle for loss in Week 5 and should be good for top-five level numbers this weekend against the Colts. Indianapolis has surrendered the most fantasy points per game to the linebacker position.

Wagner has not been producing like fantasy managers may have hoped when they drafted him, but he has still been a serviceable LB2 option. Start him as just that for a tough on-paper matchup against the Carolina Panthers.
Bolton should be a busy man in Week 6 and should have enough tackle opportunities for a top-five finish. Lock him in as an LB1 for a neutral matchup against the Bills.

Llyod has been excellent this season, forcing his way into the weekly LB1 conversation. He is a potential top-five option for a great Week 6 matchup against an Indianapolis Colts team gifting the most fantasy points to the position.
Edwards has been on fire to start the season, coming in as the LB7 overall through five weeks of play. Start him as an LB1 option for a plus Week 6 matchup against the Dallas Cowboys.
Zaire could be in line for another start with Shaq Leonard missing Wednesday's practice. Franklin should be treated as a strong LB2 option while Leonard is sidelined and started wherever possible.

Holcomb exploded in Week 5, racking up 11 solos, five assists, and one tackle for loss. The linebacker had been disappointing fantasy managers for most of the season, but his performance vaulted him into the LB2 ranks through five games.
Greenlaw has been heating up, following up on his 12 solo, three assist Week 4 with a four solo, and seven assist Week 5. Consider him a strong LB3 option with LB2 upside for Week 6.

Barton quieted changing role doubts for at least one more week, recording seven solos and five assists in Week 5. He jumped up to 77 percent from the 62 percent he saw in Week 4, but it is clear that the Seahawks intend to make their three safety package a weekly staple. This means that his snaps may fluctuate from week to week, but as long as he is seeing over 70 percent, he should be able to post low-end LB1 level numbers more often than not. Start him as an LB2 option for a plus Week 5 matchup against an Arizona Cardinals defense allowing the 15th most fantasy points to the position.

Milano the inconsistent was at it again, providing a frustrating valley after his incredible Week 5 peak. This is par for the course with the Matt Milano experience but he should bounce back against a Kansas City team allowing the eight most fantasy points per game to the position. Start him as an LB3 with obvious LB2 upside.

Singleton will see increased snaps with Josey Jewell sidelined for what looks like it will be a few weeks. This gives Singleton LB3 value during the byes. Start him as just that against the Chargers for Monday Night Football.

JOK may be in trouble if Deion Jones is activated this week. The young linebacker has been playing behind Jacob Phillips and may actually be the one who sees his snaps take a hit when Jones is active. This is a wait-and-see situation as Jones could easily just supplant Phillips instead due to his versatility, but JOK, who has hovered around the 75 percent snap mark for much of the season, can not afford to lose playing time if he is to maintain his tenuous LB2 value. The suggestion here is to keep JOK as an LB3 option only. Those who are looking for an LB2 option should look elsewhere until we learn exactly what Jones' role will be and who his snaps will come at the expense of.

Jacob Phillips exploded in Week 5, recording seven solos, three assists, one sack, and one tackle for loss. He would be on his way to locking up LB2 status for the rest of the season but the Cleveland Browns went out and traded for Deion Jones. Phillips should have another week or two of starter's snaps, but after that, it should only be a matter of time before Jones is soaking up middle linebacker snaps next to Jeremiah Owusu-Koramoah. Regardless, Phillips should be a strong producer for Week 6 and should be started as an LB2 with the byes now upon us.
Tremaine looks set to make the start against the Chiefs this weekend. He should see enough action to provide LB2 value, even if the Bills limit his snaps somewhat.

Germaine Pratt continues to reassert himself as an LB2 option, racking up two solos, six assists, one sack, one tackle for loss, and two passes defended against the Baltimore Ravens. He has put up LB1-level numbers in each of his contests this year and is going to be gold during the byes. Pratt is still behind Logan Wilson, so he is not seeing every snap, but has seen over 70 percent in three of four contests and should continue to do so as long as he is playing well. Start him as a bye-week LB2 where needed.

Morrow continues to play an every snap role for the Bears and is a strong LB2 option for a plus Week 6 matchup against a Washington Commanders team surrendering the sixth most fantasy points to the position. Start him where possible.

Jamin had four solos and two assists in Week 5, but played just 55 percent of the snaps. The production line was one of his best of the season despite the reduced snaps, but the decrease in usage is concerning for his fantasy value. Jamin drops to the LB4 range with this development. Keep him benched where possible for Thursday Night Football.

Isaiah Simmons saw a season-high 92 percent of the snaps in Week 5 and was able to parlay the playing time into production, racking up eight solos and five assists. Simmons should continue to have heavy usage while Nick Vigil remains on IR with a hamstring injury, which gives the talented hybrid a massive value increase. It was not all positive with Simmons, though, as despite playing more traditional off-ball linebacker, Simmons still spent 55 percent of his snaps in the slot while Ben Niemann manned the middle. It is clear that Vance Joseph values Simmons's length and safety skills in the slot, so this likely won't change anytime soon. With that said, Simmons is finally usable in fantasy, just in time for the byes, so feel free to fire him up for a plus matchup against the Seattle Seahawks. View him as an LB2 option for Week 6.

Kwon finally turned his heavy snap role into fantasy production, racking up six solos, four assists, and one tackle for loss. He has played over 92 percent of the snaps in consecutive weeks and appears to be set to see at least 85 percent of the snaps going forward. Kwon is an excellent LB3 option during the byes, who can creep into the LB2 discussion during great matchups. Kwon is an LB3 option for a neutral Week 6 matchup against the Green Bay Packers.

Gary has been on fire this season and will look to keep the good times rolling against a New York Jets team allowing the sixth most fantasy points to opposing edge rushers. Start him as a top-five DL option for Week 6.

Matt Judon was strong again in Week 5, racking up two solos, one assist, two sacks, two tackles for loss, and one forced fumble. Judon has been on fire this season, tied for first in the league with six sacks. Judon has at least one sack in every game this season and will look to make it six games in a row against the Cleveland Browns this weekend. Treat Judon as a borderline DL1/LB2 option for the plus matchup.

Andersen is slated to get the start this weekend for injured LB1 option Mykal Walker. He is stepping into a role that lends itself to high IDP production, making him an LB3 with LB2 just based on opportunity alone. Start Andersen where needed.

Now up to 5.5 sacks on the season, Bradley Chubb needs to be started universally during the byes. He went off in Week 5, with four solos, three assists, 2.5 sacks, one tackle for loss, and one forced fumble. He does carry the unfortunate LB-only designation at Yahoo, but should still be rostered as an LB3 or a bye-week filler for your LB2. Chubb has never quite recreated the magic of his record approaching rookie season, but if, at his current pace, he stays healthy, he should be able to threaten his career highs of 12.5 sacks and 36 pressures. Chubb should be started where possible.

Von Miller should inch closer to the 70 percent snap mark he sees in competitive contests this weekend against Kansas City. The increased snaps give Von DL1 value for a plus Week 6 matchup against a Chiefs team surrendering the ninth most fantasy points to the defensive end position.

Quinn has just one sack and five pressures all season, making him a DL3 option for Week 6 despite a wonderful matchup against a Washington offensive line that has had its struggles this season. Keep him benched for Thursday Night Football if you are only required to start two or fewer DL's per week.
Dodson is back to being a bench or bye-week piece, with Tremaine Edmunds and Matt Milano both expected to be active for Week 6. Look elsewhere if you are in need of bye-week LB help.
Golden has zero sacks and just one tackle for loss on the season. He belongs on the waiver wire in leagues with fewer than 16+ teams.

Browning went off in Week 5, racking up two solos, three assists, 1.5 sacks, two tackles for loss, and six QB hits. He proved that he is more than ready to play starters snaps with Randy Gregory sidelined and is an immediate DL3 with DL2 upside for a plus matchup against a banged up Chargers offensive line.

Ebukam is set to see an expanded role with Arik Armstead sidelined and Nick Bosa dealing with an injury. He led the team in edge snaps with Bosa knocked out of Week 5's contest and should see 60-80 percent of the snaps for the next few weeks.

Sneed is the DB1 through five weeks of play and needs to be started universally as a DB1 option. Sneed is an elite IDP option regardless of position for a Week 6 matchup against a Bills offense allowing the fifth most fantasy points to the cornerback position.

Hufanga, the DB4 overall on the season, was excellent again in Week 5, tallying two solos, three assists, one sack, one tackle for loss, and one pass defended. The young safety is only getting better and should be considered a top-five option at his position for Week 6.

There is major risk that the DB7 on the season is going to be his snaps scaled back, perhaps drastically, with Jayron Kearse healthy. There was enough on the plate for all three safeties to eat in Week 5, primarily because the Cowboys used frequent three safety looks, but if this changes, it may very well be Wilson who suffers. This makes Wilson a DB2 with a DB4 floor going forward.

Julian Love was excellent in Week 5, racking up six solos, one assist, one tackle for loss, and one forced fumble. Love has played every snap in four of five games this season and has four contests with four or more solos. Love is likely long gone in CB leagues, but it is well past time that we start viewing him as a DB2 option, especially when he has great matchups like he does this week. He will get the Baltimore Ravens in Week 6, a team surrendering the ninth most fantasy points to the position.

Brandon Jones went off in Week 5, tallying five solos, four assists, one sack, and one tackle for loss. Jones saw 97 percent of the snaps in Week 5, a week after seeing just 39 percent against Cincinnati Bengals. It seems like his snaps may be inconsistent, as he has seen over 90 percent of the snaps in three of his five games, with a 64 percent share and the aforementioned 39 percent also in the mix. Jones is a better pure talent than Eric Rowe, but there must be some packages they prefer Rowe in. Regardless, Jones is back in the DB2 mix for the byes, including this week against the Minnesota Vikings. The matchup is not a good one in terms of fantasy points against, but Jones will see heavy snaps in the box, making the 12 solos we saw from the Bears safeties a comfortable floor to project Jones and Jevon Holland hitting this week. Start Holland as a DB1 option where possible.

Kearse saw starter snaps in his first game back thanks to the Cowboys utilizing heavy three safety dime package looks. JK is going to be top two in snaps before long, so it may come at the expense of Donovan Wilson. This is a situation to monitor.

Kyle Dugger was excellent in Week 5, racking up one solo, four assists, one tackle for loss, one fumble recovery, and one touchdown. He played just 58 percent of the snaps for the second straight week, but his performance against the Lions suggests that he is rounding back into form. Whether or not this means that he recaptures the 85 percent snap role he saw to start the season remains to be seen. With that said, Dugger is a DB1 option when he is seeing over 80 percent of the snaps, so he should still get some DB2 love when he is hovering around the 60 percent mark. View him as a DB2 option for a plus Week 6 matchup against a Cleveland team allowing the 14th most fantasy points per game to the position.

CJGJ broke out in Week 5, recording 10 solos, one tackle for loss, one interception, and one pass defended. This is the type of game fantasy managers were waitng all season for, making now the time to start the talented safety going forward. He is a DB2 option during the byes and should be started as just that for a plus Week 6 matchup against a Dallas Cowboys team relinquishing the 17th most fantasy points to the position.

Josh Jones has been benched in favor of Ryan Neal. The Seahawks seem to be shifting away from the three safety looks they were using to get Neal on the field n favor of keeping him on the field over Jones. Bench Jones until further notice. Those in shallower leagues can drop him altogether.

Ryan Neal has outplayed Josh Jones and is now seeing starters snaps for the Seahawks. He played almost half of his snaps in the box in Week 5 and should see similar usage going forward. This new role puts Neal in the DB2 conversation on a weekly basis.

Burris recorded six solos, two assists, and one pass defended in Week 5, and looks like he will boast solid DB3 value for as long as Jeremy Chinn is sidelined. Start Burris where needed for a plus matchup against the Los Angeles Rams.

Those looking for safety help for Week 6 should look no further than Geno Stone. Still available in most leagues, Stone is set to start next to Chuck Clark while Marcus Williams is sidelined with a dislocated wrist. As we will discuss more below, Kyle Hamilton is a threat to steal some of these snaps, but it is Stone who got the nod when Williams went down with the injury, not Hamilton. Stone, noted for his versatility when coming into the league, can become an instant IDP force, especially if they deploy him like they did Williams, the DB4 overall, despite missing half of Week 5. You will likely not need to plug him in as anything more than a DB3 for Week 6, but Stone is a sneaky DB2 option for a plus matchup against a New York Giants team surrendering the 10th most fantasy points to the position.
Keanu goes from sit to start due to both Mike Edwards and Logan Ryan being ruled out for Week 6. Plug Keanu in as a DB2 with DB1 upside for a plus matchup against the Pittsburgh Steelers.

The hope was that Kyle Hamilton would jump into a starter's role with Marcus Williams sidelined with a dislocated wrist, but instead, it looks like it will be Geno Stone that gets the tap. Hamilton played just 22 percent of the snaps in Week 5, his lowest mark of the season. Stone saw 56 percent of the snaps and should be closer to 90 percent this week. The talented rookie will become an IDP force when he finally settles in as a starter, but he is going to be hard to trust until then. He has too much upside to drop, so keep Hamilton benched where roster sizes allow.
